article.headline: Milwaukee 100, Boston 94
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Paul Pierce's uncharacteristic struggles from the free throw line worked out for the Milwaukee Bucks. Joe Smith made two free throws with 11 seconds left and Toni Kukoc scored nine fourth-quarter points to lead the Bucks past the Boston Celtics 100-94, in the second game of a home-and-home series between the teams. With Boston trailing 96-93, Pierce was fouled by Smith while taking a 3-pointer with 12 seconds to go, but missed two of three free throws. Pierce, an 89 percent free throw shooter coming in, missed 5-of-8 from the line. "Obviously, someone of that stature, you thought for sure he'd make those three and we'd be in overtime," Milwaukee coach Terry Porter said. "We were fortunate tonight that he didn't make his free throws." After a timeout, Boston fouled Smith, who sank both free throws for a 98-94 lead. Smith said he didn't think he fouled Pierce on the earlier play, but was surprised when the Celtics star missed. "It worked out for us, and gave us an opportunity to win it with free throws of our own," said Smith, who had 16 points and 11 rebounds. Vin Baker missed a 3-pointer, and Michael Redd hit a pair of free throws for the final margin. Milwaukee blew a 15-point second-quarter lead, fell behind by 12 in the third quarter and rallied to become the first team to score 100 points against the Celtics this season. "We failed to defend them in the fourth quarter," Pierce said. "In the fourth quarter is when you should be playing your best team defense. Tonight, we let down in the fourth." Redd had 23 points, Desmond Mason had a season-high 22 points for Milwaukee, which scored 62 points in the second half. "We didn't play good defense for most of the (fourth) quarter," said Boston's Mike James, who had a career-high 23 points. Pierce scored 21 for the Celtics, which beat the Bucks 106-96 Friday night in Boston. Boston opened its biggest lead, 58-46, on James' 3-pointer with 7:34 left in the third quarter. Milwaukee's defense was strong early and the Bucks opened a 34-19 lead on Erick Strickland's 3-pointer with 5:59 left in the second quarter. The Bucks didn't make another field goal until the third quarter, and Boston ran off 19 consecutive points to take a 38-34 lead on James' 3-pointer with 2:01 left in the quarter.

Game notes
Pierce left the game with 10:04 left in the third quarter with an injury to his left hand. He returned with 7:49 left in the quarter. ... Bucks F Tim Thomas missed his second consecutive game with a sprained ankle. Mason started in his place. ... James previous career high was 20 points on March 20 with Miami against Dallas. ... The Celtics came into the game shooting 29 percent on 3-pointers, but were 12-of-24 against the Bucks.
